  const articleHtml = "<article><div class=\"m\"><div class=\"m\"><span class=\"m\"></span><section><div><div class=\"er ge gf gg gh gi\"></div><div class=\"gj gk gl gm gn\"><div class=\"ac ci\"><div class=\"cp bi fv fw fx fy\"><div><div></div></div><p class=\"pw-post-body-paragraph lx ly gq lz b ma mb mc md me mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms mt mu gj bl\" id=\"ef53\"></p><figure class=\"mz na nb nc nd ne mw mx paragraph-image\"><div class=\"nf ng eo nh bi ni\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><div class=\"mw mx my\"><picture><source sizes=\"(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px\" srcset=\"https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/0*LtYY2SMZueHLRi5q 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/0*LtYY2SMZueHLRi5q 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/0*LtYY2SMZueHLRi5q 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/0*LtYY2SMZueHLRi5q 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/0*LtYY2SMZueHLRi5q 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/0*LtYY2SMZueHLRi5q 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/0*LtYY2SMZueHLRi5q 1400w\" type=\"image/webp\"/><source data-testid=\"og\" sizes=\"(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px\" srcset=\"https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/0*LtYY2SMZueHLRi5q 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/0*LtYY2SMZueHLRi5q 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/0*LtYY2SMZueHLRi5q 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/0*LtYY2SMZueHLRi5q 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/0*LtYY2SMZueHLRi5q 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/0*LtYY2SMZueHLRi5q 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/0*LtYY2SMZueHLRi5q 1400w\"/><img alt=\"\" class=\"bi lh nj c\" height=\"356\" loading=\"eager\" role=\"presentation\" width=\"700\"/></picture></div></div><figcaption class=\"nk nl nm mw mx nn no bg b bh ab ee\">Photo credit: <a class=\"ah np\" href=\"https://www.vamprogram.hu/en/-/we-have-developed-our-ai-speech-recognition-solution-optimized-for-the-hungarian-language\" rel=\"noopener ugc nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.vamprogram.hu/en/-/we-have-developed-our-ai-speech-recognition-solution-optimized-for-the-hungarian-language</a></figcaption></figure><h2 class=\"nq nr gq bg ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol om on bl\" id=\"4178\">Introduction</h2><p class=\"pw-post-body-paragraph lx ly gq lz b ma oo mc md me op mg mh mi oq mk ml mm or mo mp mq os ms mt mu gj bl\" id=\"643e\">Have you ever heard the phrase \u201chow the sausage is made\u201d? If you\u2019ve been as passionate as me about this great little language game, the rest of this post might ruin some of its magic. Here\u2019s the story of how I found a way to solve every Wordle puzzle, once and for all.</p><p class=\"pw-post-body-paragraph lx ly gq lz b ma mb mc md me mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms mt mu gj bl\" id=\"bf38\">When <a class=\"ah np\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Josh_Wardle\" rel=\"noopener ugc nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Josh Wardle</a>\u2019s \u201c<a class=\"ah np\" href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/games/wordle/index.html\" rel=\"noopener ugc nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Wordle</a>\u201d broke the scene in 2021, I, like many other people, became obsessed with it. Growing up in a multicultural and multilingual family, having always had a passion for language and data, and coming to the end of my undergraduate degree studying languages, Wordle was the perfect thing to unconsciously further my interest in quantitative linguistics. My whole family played it, and it had become routine to wake up and see messages in our extended-family group chat, where my Chilean grandparents had even already completed not just the English Wordle of the day, but also the Spanish and German versions of the game, first thing in the morning. This went on for months, everyone comparing our solutions and discussing how we got there. After playing the game for some time without thinking too deeply into it, one thing still became clear to me: there definitely seemed to be some logic \u2014 even abstractly, for what constituted a \u2018good\u2019 solution, and a \u2018bad\u2019 one.</p><p class=\"pw-post-body-paragraph lx ly gq lz b ma mb mc md me mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms mt mu gj bl\" id=\"eb9b\">Fast-forward to April 2022, I got accepted into the <a class=\"ah np\" href=\"https://masterdatascience.ubc.ca/programs/computational-linguistics\" rel=\"noopener ugc nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">University of British Columbia\u2019s Master of Data Science \u2014 Computational Linguistics</a> program, and though I didn\u2019t yet have much coding experience under my belt, finding a method to solve all Wordle puzzles, in the same way, seemed like a perfect match for the skills I would acquire in my upcoming studies, so the idea gained even more of my attention.</p><p class=\"pw-post-body-paragraph lx ly gq lz b ma mb mc md me mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms mt mu gj bl\" id=\"eddd\">After I moved across the country and began the program, I naturally felt my world turn upside-down, which included letting go of my daily Wordle attempts, and it fell out of mind for a long while. It wasn\u2019t until February of this year (2023) that it suddenly slipped back into my head again, and I thought, with everything I had learned in my current studies, surely I could now figure it out. Coincidentally, reading week was right around the corner, so I spent my week off doing exactly this.</p><h2 class=\"nq nr gq bg ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol om on bl\" id=\"f34f\">Review of Game Mechanics</h2><p class=\"pw-post-body-paragraph lx ly gq lz b ma oo mc md me op mg mh mi oq mk ml mm or mo mp mq os ms mt mu gj bl\" id=\"9c10\">Before getting into exactly how I did this, we have to review exactly how Wordle works. In six guesses or less, we have to figure out some unknown five-letter target word. How do we do this? By guessing other five-letter words. After each guess, we get feedback on our guess. For each letter of the word, the letter appears in a box coloured according to the following checks:</p><ul class=\"\"><li class=\"lx ly gq lz b ma mb mc md me mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms mt mu ot ou ov bl\" id=\"9ac0\"><strong class=\"lz gr\"><em class=\"mv\">Green</em></strong> if the letter is the correct letter, in the correct position</li><li class=\"lx ly gq lz b ma ow mc md me ox mg mh mi oy mk ml mm oz mo mp mq pa ms mt mu ot ou ov bl\" id=\"f6a3\"><strong class=\"lz gr\"><em class=\"mv\">Yellow</em></strong> if the letter is in fact in the target word, but currently in the incorrect position</li><li class=\"lx ly gq lz b ma ow mc md me ox mg mh mi oy mk ml mm oz mo mp mq pa ms mt mu ot ou ov bl\" id=\"aece\"><strong class=\"lz gr\"><em class=\"mv\">Grey</em></strong> if the letter is not in the target word whatsoever</li></ul><p class=\"pw-post-body-paragraph lx ly gq lz b ma mb mc md me mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms mt mu gj bl\" id=\"99aa\">In the case below, the target word was \u201cHORSE\u201d, and we can see the player get iteratively closer with each guess, as they learn more information about the target from these three checks.</p><figure class=\"mz na nb nc nd ne mw mx paragraph-image\"><div class=\"mw mx pb\"><picture><source sizes=\"(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 301px\" srcset=\"https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*bAysUJmtDA1WDBnFu0GH1w.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*bAysUJmtDA1WDBnFu0GH1w.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*bAysUJmtDA1WDBnFu0GH1w.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*bAysUJmtDA1WDBnFu0GH1w.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*bAysUJmtDA1WDBnFu0GH1w.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*bAysUJmtDA1WDBnFu0GH1w.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:602/format:webp/1*bAysUJmtDA1WDBnFu0GH1w.png 602w\" type=\"image/webp\"/><source data-testid=\"og\" sizes=\"(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 301px\" srcset=\"https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*bAysUJmtDA1WDBnFu0GH1w.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*bAysUJmtDA1WDBnFu0GH1w.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*bAysUJmtDA1WDBnFu0GH1w.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*bAysUJmtDA1WDBnFu0GH1w.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*bAysUJmtDA1WDBnFu0GH1w.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*bAysUJmtDA1WDBnFu0GH1w.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:602/1*bAysUJmtDA1WDBnFu0GH1w.png 602w\"/><img alt=\"\" class=\"bi lh nj c\" height=\"508\" loading=\"lazy\" role=\"presentation\" width=\"301\"/></picture></div><figcaption class=\"nk nl nm mw mx nn no bg b bh ab ee\">Image captured by author</figcaption></figure><p class=\"pw-post-body-paragraph lx ly gq lz b ma mb mc md me mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms mt mu gj bl\" id=\"397a\">Before explaining my process, I would like to note that though I acknowledge there are multiple ways to do this \u2014 the most popular of which seems to be using Information Theory (if you\u2019re interested in seeing exactly how this can be applied to Wordle, see <a class=\"ah np\" href=\"https://www.youtube.com/@3blue1brown\" rel=\"noopener ugc nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">3Blue1Brown\u2019s</a> video on it, <a class=\"ah np\" href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v68zYyaEmEA\" rel=\"noopener ugc nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>), I wanted to try to solve it on my own, without any outside resources or references. Not knowing much about Information Theory at this time, here\u2019s how I solved Wordle using only basic concepts from probability.</p><h2 class=\"nq nr gq bg ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol om on bl\" id=\"843b\">My Solution</h2><p class=\"pw-post-body-paragraph lx ly gq lz b ma oo mc md me op mg mh mi oq mk ml mm or mo mp mq os ms mt mu gj bl\" id=\"edd2\">At its core, the game consists of a list of ~2300 words (I\u2019ve seen multiple sizes, depending on the source \u2014 the list I used had 2309), to which we can safely limit our domain since the game doesn\u2019t allow us to guess words outside of this list. In a puzzle, after our first guess, assuming this guess was not exactly the target word, even if we do away with all letter feedback of the guess and just randomly guess a new word from all remaining words in the list, we are guaranteed to guess the target word within 2309 total guesses (the total number of words in the list). Of course, this is an exaggerated example, as this method would fail the official puzzle rules (a maximum of six guesses) most of the time, but as there are many very similar words in the list, even if we have considerable information about the target word based on cumulative feedback, it can still take several guesses to get to the target. For example, there are five words that all end in <em class=\"mv\">-olly</em>: <em class=\"mv\">jolly</em>, <em class=\"mv\">holly</em>, <em class=\"mv\">molly</em>, <em class=\"mv\">dolly</em>, and <em class=\"mv\">folly</em> (what I call \u201cThe Jolly Problem\u201d). Even if we know that the word ends in <em class=\"mv\">-olly</em>, if we haven\u2019t already guessed one or more of these words, it is statistically extremely unlikely that we\u2019ll guess that target before we reach the maximum number of guesses. This introduces something I quickly realized I wanted to avoid: <em class=\"mv\">luck</em>. What makes The Jolly Problem so significant is not limited to just words similar to <em class=\"mv\">jolly</em>, (there are 141 words that end in <em class=\"mv\">-er</em>), so even if you haven\u2019t played the game and felt like the embodiment of the facepalm emoji because your last three guesses were all one letter away from the target word, the fact that this remains a very case-by-case basis meant I wanted to avoid it, and instead focus on a method that would be much more robust. My leading idea for a more reliable method was then centred around how to consistently maximize the value of each guess, which would theoretically ultimately get me to the target word much sooner than relying on something founded in <em class=\"mv\">luck.</em></p><p class=\"pw-post-body-paragraph lx ly gq lz b ma mb mc md me mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms mt mu gj bl\" id=\"0922\">The first thing I did was make a frequency distribution of each letter in the word list. That looks like this:</p><figure class=\"mz na nb nc nd ne mw mx paragraph-image\"><div class=\"nf ng eo nh bi ni\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><div class=\"mw mx pc\"><picture><source sizes=\"(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px\" srcset=\"https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*oqmySZTe5m5ufjHAGrbu0A.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*oqmySZTe5m5ufjHAGrbu0A.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*oqmySZTe5m5ufjHAGrbu0A.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*oqmySZTe5m5ufjHAGrbu0A.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*oqmySZTe5m5ufjHAGrbu0A.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*oqmySZTe5m5ufjHAGrbu0A.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/1*oqmySZTe5m5ufjHAGrbu0A.png 1400w\" type=\"image/webp\"/><source data-testid=\"og\" sizes=\"(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px\" srcset=\"https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*oqmySZTe5m5ufjHAGrbu0A.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*oqmySZTe5m5ufjHAGrbu0A.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*oqmySZTe5m5ufjHAGrbu0A.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*oqmySZTe5m5ufjHAGrbu0A.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*oqmySZTe5m5ufjHAGrbu0A.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*oqmySZTe5m5ufjHAGrbu0A.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*oqmySZTe5m5ufjHAGrbu0A.png 1400w\"/><img alt=\"\" class=\"bi lh nj c\" height=\"275\" loading=\"lazy\" role=\"presentation\" width=\"700\"/></picture></div></div><figcaption class=\"nk nl nm mw mx nn no bg b bh ab ee\">Image generated by author</figcaption></figure><p class=\"pw-post-body-paragraph lx ly gq lz b ma mb mc md me mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms mt mu gj bl\" id=\"63bc\">Making this is straightforward. For each word in the list, I looked at the unique letters of the word (I explain this decision in the following paragraph), and incremented the count of each unique letter by 1 if they appeared in the word.</p><p class=\"pw-post-body-paragraph lx ly gq lz b ma mb mc md me mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms mt mu gj bl\" id=\"fb3b\">After playing the game for so long without trying to formally analyze it, I already had a suspicion that certain starting words were \u2018better\u2019 than others. I liked to use <em class=\"mv\">audio</em> because it has 4 vowels (which typically show up more frequently in words than consonants) and because I have a background in music and music production, and everyone I knew had their own favourite starting word, for one reason or another. I couldn\u2019t yet prove that <em class=\"mv\">audio</em> was a better guess than another word, but I intuitively assumed this because I would typically solve puzzles more quickly with a word like <em class=\"mv\">audio</em> than one like <em class=\"mv\">puppy</em>.</p><p class=\"pw-post-body-paragraph lx ly gq lz b ma mb mc md me mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms mt mu gj bl\" id=\"62e6\">The reason I used only unique letters in each word was that I didn\u2019t think that a word like <em class=\"mv\">puppy</em>, with three <em class=\"mv\">p</em>\u2019s, added much extra information about the target guess by having more than one p. Just based on my own experience playing the game, I often got to the target word in fewer guesses when I guessed words with a higher letter diversity than when I began with one of a lower letter diversity.</p><p class=\"pw-post-body-paragraph lx ly gq lz b ma mb mc md me mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms mt mu gj bl\" id=\"74b7\">Next, I came up with a simple metric by which I could \u2018rate\u2019 each word. Using each letter of the letter distribution and its corresponding count, I again looked at each word, and for each unique letter in the word, I:</p><ul class=\"\"><li class=\"lx ly gq lz b ma mb mc md me mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms mt mu ot ou ov bl\" id=\"7fc8\">summed the unique letters\u2019 counts according to the frequency distribution</li><li class=\"lx ly gq lz b ma ow mc md me ox mg mh mi oy mk ml mm oz mo mp mq pa ms mt mu ot ou ov bl\" id=\"915d\">divided this by the sum of the counts of all letters of the frequency distribution</li><li class=\"lx ly gq lz b ma ow mc md me ox mg mh mi oy mk ml mm oz mo mp mq pa ms mt mu ot ou ov bl\" id=\"c74d\">multiply the resulting value by 100</li></ul><figure class=\"mz na nb nc nd ne mw mx paragraph-image\"><div class=\"nf ng eo nh bi ni\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><div class=\"mw mx pd\"><picture><source sizes=\"(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px\" srcset=\"https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*OEJnO04EPolsusP07qzgAw.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*OEJnO04EPolsusP07qzgAw.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*OEJnO04EPolsusP07qzgAw.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*OEJnO04EPolsusP07qzgAw.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*OEJnO04EPolsusP07qzgAw.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*OEJnO04EPolsusP07qzgAw.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/1*OEJnO04EPolsusP07qzgAw.png 1400w\" type=\"image/webp\"/><source data-testid=\"og\" sizes=\"(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px\" srcset=\"https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*OEJnO04EPolsusP07qzgAw.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*OEJnO04EPolsusP07qzgAw.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*OEJnO04EPolsusP07qzgAw.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*OEJnO04EPolsusP07qzgAw.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*OEJnO04EPolsusP07qzgAw.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*OEJnO04EPolsusP07qzgAw.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*OEJnO04EPolsusP07qzgAw.png 1400w\"/><img alt=\"\" class=\"bi lh nj c\" height=\"146\" loading=\"lazy\" role=\"presentation\" width=\"700\"/></picture></div></div><figcaption class=\"nk nl nm mw mx nn no bg b bh ab ee\">Relative frequency of unique letters from a given word. Image generated by author.</figcaption></figure><p class=\"pw-post-body-paragraph lx ly gq lz b ma mb mc md me mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms mt mu gj bl\" id=\"5ba4\">I think of it as an answer to the question: <em class=\"mv\">in how many words of the entire word list, do the letters of a given word appear?</em> As an example, the rating for <strong class=\"lz gr\"><em class=\"mv\">later</em></strong> can be found as follows:</p><p class=\"pw-post-body-paragraph lx ly gq lz b ma mb mc md me mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms mt mu gj bl\" id=\"68fe\">Unique letters: L, A, T, E, R<br/>Count of each <em class=\"mv\">unique</em> letter from the distribution:</p><p class=\"pw-post-body-paragraph lx ly gq lz b ma mb mc md me mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms mt mu gj bl\" id=\"83cd\"><strong class=\"lz gr\"><em class=\"mv\">L</em></strong><em class=\"mv\"> = 645, </em><strong class=\"lz gr\"><em class=\"mv\">A</em></strong><em class=\"mv\"> = 906, </em><strong class=\"lz gr\"><em class=\"mv\">T</em></strong><em class=\"mv\"> = 667, </em><strong class=\"lz gr\"><em class=\"mv\">E</em></strong><em class=\"mv\"> = 1053, </em><strong class=\"lz gr\"><em class=\"mv\">R</em></strong><em class=\"mv\"> = 835</em></p><p class=\"pw-post-body-paragraph lx ly gq lz b ma mb mc md me mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms mt mu gj bl\" id=\"4f70\">Sum of the counts of <em class=\"mv\">all</em> letters: 10739 (this is less than 5 x 2309 because we\u2019re only counting unique letters \u2014 duplicates are not included)</p><p class=\"pw-post-body-paragraph lx ly gq lz b ma mb mc md me mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms mt mu gj bl\" id=\"34d6\">Sum of <em class=\"mv\">later</em>\u2019s unique letters\u2019 counts: <em class=\"mv\">645 + 906 + 667 + 1053 + 853 = 4124</em><br/>Sum of <em class=\"mv\">later</em>\u2019s unique letters\u2019 counts divided by all letters\u2019 counts:</p><p class=\"pw-post-body-paragraph lx ly gq lz b ma mb mc md me mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms mt mu gj bl\" id=\"6b62\"><em class=\"mv\">4124/10739 * 100 = </em><strong class=\"lz gr\"><em class=\"mv\">~38.23</em></strong></p><p class=\"pw-post-body-paragraph lx ly gq lz b ma mb mc md me mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms mt mu gj bl\" id=\"e6b3\">We can apply the same logic to get the rating of <strong class=\"lz gr\"><em class=\"mv\">puppy</em></strong>, like this:</p><p class=\"pw-post-body-paragraph lx ly gq lz b ma mb mc md me mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms mt mu gj bl\" id=\"557f\">Unique letters: P, U, Y <em class=\"mv\">\u2192 note that it has significantly fewer unique letters</em><br/>Count of each unique letter from the distribution:</p><p class=\"pw-post-body-paragraph lx ly gq lz b ma mb mc md me mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms mt mu gj bl\" id=\"2720\"><strong class=\"lz gr\"><em class=\"mv\">P</em></strong><em class=\"mv\"> = 345, </em><strong class=\"lz gr\"><em class=\"mv\">U</em></strong><em class=\"mv\"> = 456, </em><strong class=\"lz gr\"><em class=\"mv\">Y</em></strong><em class=\"mv\"> = 416</em></p><p class=\"pw-post-body-paragraph lx ly gq lz b ma mb mc md me mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms mt mu gj bl\" id=\"bd8f\">Sum of the counts of <em class=\"mv\">all</em> letters: <em class=\"mv\">10739</em> (reminder that this is less than <em class=\"mv\">5 x 2309</em> because we\u2019re only counting unique letters \u2014 duplicates are not included)</p><p class=\"pw-post-body-paragraph lx ly gq lz b ma mb mc md me mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms mt mu gj bl\" id=\"1042\">Sum of <em class=\"mv\">puppy</em>\u2019s unique letters\u2019 counts: <em class=\"mv\">345 + 456 + 416 = 1217</em><br/>Sum of <em class=\"mv\">puppy</em>\u2019s unique letters\u2019 counts divided by all letters\u2019 counts:</p><p class=\"pw-post-body-paragraph lx ly gq lz b ma mb mc md me mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms mt mu gj bl\" id=\"8b6f\"><em class=\"mv\">1217/10739 * 100 = </em><strong class=\"lz gr\"><em class=\"mv\">~11.33</em></strong></p><p class=\"pw-post-body-paragraph lx ly gq lz b ma mb mc md me mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms mt mu gj bl\" id=\"d816\">Given this rating, the unique letters of <em class=\"mv\">later</em> show up in about 38% of all words in the word list. That means that if you use <em class=\"mv\">later</em> as a starting guess in a game, you have about a 38% chance that you\u2019ll get at least one yellow letter (or better), whereas the chance of the same happening for starting with <em class=\"mv\">puppy</em> is only about 11%. Does this mean that <em class=\"mv\">later</em> is more than 3x as good of a word choice as <em class=\"mv\">puppy</em>? Not quite. But now that I had a rating for each word, I had an idea of theoretically how well words should perform, compared to one another.</p><figure class=\"mz na nb nc nd ne mw mx paragraph-image\"><div class=\"nf ng eo nh bi ni\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><div class=\"mw mx pc\"><picture><source sizes=\"(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px\" srcset=\"https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*HxN-ew3Kcme_JSoYN0UgmA.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*HxN-ew3Kcme_JSoYN0UgmA.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*HxN-ew3Kcme_JSoYN0UgmA.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*HxN-ew3Kcme_JSoYN0UgmA.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*HxN-ew3Kcme_JSoYN0UgmA.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*HxN-ew3Kcme_JSoYN0UgmA.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/1*HxN-ew3Kcme_JSoYN0UgmA.png 1400w\" type=\"image/webp\"/><source data-testid=\"og\" sizes=\"(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px\" srcset=\"https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*HxN-ew3Kcme_JSoYN0UgmA.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*HxN-ew3Kcme_JSoYN0UgmA.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*HxN-ew3Kcme_JSoYN0UgmA.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*HxN-ew3Kcme_JSoYN0UgmA.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*HxN-ew3Kcme_JSoYN0UgmA.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*HxN-ew3Kcme_JSoYN0UgmA.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*HxN-ew3Kcme_JSoYN0UgmA.png 1400w\"/><img alt=\"\" class=\"bi lh nj c\" height=\"275\" loading=\"lazy\" role=\"presentation\" width=\"700\"/></picture></div></div><figcaption class=\"nk nl nm mw mx nn no bg b bh ab ee\">Image generated by author</figcaption></figure><p class=\"pw-post-body-paragraph lx ly gq lz b ma mb mc md me mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms mt mu gj bl\" id=\"18c8\">Now that a rating has been calculated for each word and we can rank words according to their ratings, the task of automatically getting from any given start word to any given target word is actually very simple. Remember those three types of feedback we can get from every guess? In a solution, before the first guess is passed, the number of words the target word could possibly be is the entire list \u2014 2309 in this case. After the first guess, the algorithm subsets the list of possible guesses to only those that satisfy the information given to us about the first guess, and then chooses its next guess word by looking at the ratings of each word in the list of all remaining words, and simply chooses the word with the highest rating. Rinse and repeat, and it typically finds the target word by the fourth guess.</p><h2 class=\"nq nr gq bg ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol om on bl\" id=\"96b3\">Results</h2><p class=\"pw-post-body-paragraph lx ly gq lz b ma oo mc md me op mg mh mi oq mk ml mm or mo mp mq os ms mt mu gj bl\" id=\"70e1\">To empirically test these ratings, I selected a handful of words (as testing all 2309 words would take days to compute \u2014 which I don\u2019t have available to me at the moment, though I hope to do this at some point) as starting words, trying to solve every single word in the Wordle list I was using. Below is a distribution of the number of guesses each of <em class=\"mv\">later</em>, <em class=\"mv\">login</em>, and <em class=\"mv\">fuzzy</em> as the starting word, against this list (including the word, itself, which is why there\u2019s a single data point <em class=\"mv\">x = 1 </em>in each distribution).</p><figure class=\"mz na nb nc nd ne mw mx paragraph-image\"><div class=\"nf ng eo nh bi ni\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><div class=\"mw mx pc\"><picture><source sizes=\"(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px\" srcset=\"https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*oGfGN2nR9W1PM4ELEz042A.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*oGfGN2nR9W1PM4ELEz042A.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*oGfGN2nR9W1PM4ELEz042A.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*oGfGN2nR9W1PM4ELEz042A.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*oGfGN2nR9W1PM4ELEz042A.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*oGfGN2nR9W1PM4ELEz042A.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/1*oGfGN2nR9W1PM4ELEz042A.png 1400w\" type=\"image/webp\"/><source data-testid=\"og\" sizes=\"(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px\" srcset=\"https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*oGfGN2nR9W1PM4ELEz042A.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*oGfGN2nR9W1PM4ELEz042A.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*oGfGN2nR9W1PM4ELEz042A.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*oGfGN2nR9W1PM4ELEz042A.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*oGfGN2nR9W1PM4ELEz042A.png 828w, htt